SIMPLE: piteous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Piteous
<hw>Pit"e*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pitous</ets>, OF. <ets>pitos</ets>, F. <ets>piteux</ets>. See
<er>Pity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pious; devout.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord can deliver <qex>piteous</qex> men from temptation.</q>
<rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Evincing pity, compassion, or sympathy;
compassionate; tender.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧[She] <xex>piteous</xex> of his
case.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was so charitable and so <qex>pitous</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fitted to excite pity or sympathy; wretched;
miserable; lamentable; sad; <as>as, a <ex>piteous</ex> case</as>.</def>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The most <qex>piteous</qex> tale of Lear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Paltry; mean; pitiful.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Piteous</xex> amends.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sorrowful; mournful; affecting; doleful; woeful;
rueful; sad; wretched; miserable; pitiable; pitiful;
compassionate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pit"e*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pit"e*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pitfall</ent>⟦br⟧
